Appendix A Extended Soundness Proof
Full Proof of Theorem 3.1.
Let be a PPT adversary that produces an accepting composite proof for input and claimed output .
Define the honest computation sequence and the adversary’s claimed sequence . Since , at least one of the following holds:
Case 1: Hidden state deviation. Let be the first layer with incorrect output. For , we have , so commitments match: . At layer , the proof claims: . But by assumption , so proves a false statement. By layer- soundness, this occurs with probability at most .
Case 2: No hidden state deviation but output mismatch. If for all but , then proves incorrect output computation, which by the output layer’s soundness occurs with probability at most .
Case 3: Commitment collision. If hidden states match but commitments differ somewhere in the chain, the adversary has found with but —a collision in . By collision resistance, this occurs with probability at most .
By union bound over layer proofs and potential collision points: . For Halo2 IPA with , each , and SHA-256 collision resistance gives . For : . ∎
Appendix B Approximation Details
Each non-arithmetic operation is replaced by a -entry lookup table (LUT) over a fixed operating range. During ZK circuit evaluation, the prover quantizes the input to 16-bit fixed-point, retrieves the precomputed output from the table, and proves correctness of the lookup via Plookup-style range constraints (Gabizon et al., 2019). Below we detail the construction for each operation.
Softmax. For attention scores in , we build a lookup table for . The softmax is then computed as , where the division is implemented as a multiplication by the precomputed reciprocal. The range covers of attention logit values in practice; out-of-range values are clamped. Maximum absolute error: . This error is negligible because softmax normalizes over all entries, causing per-entry errors to partially cancel.
GELU. Direct lookup for with entries. Values outside this range use the asymptotic behavior of GELU: for and for , both of which are exact in the limit and can be represented as simple arithmetic constraints without lookup. Maximum absolute error within the lookup range: .
SiLU. Used by TinyLLaMA and other LLaMA-family models in place of GELU. Direct lookup for ; same asymptotic handling as GELU. Maximum absolute error: .
RMSNorm. We precompute (reciprocal square root) for , covering the typical range of mean-squared activations. An optional Newton-Raphson refinement step () can reduce the quantization error from to when higher precision is needed, at the cost of one additional multiplication constraint in the circuit. Maximum absolute error without refinement: .
Appendix C Additional Experimental Data
C.1 MLP Scaling Analysis
Table 6 reports standalone Halo2 IPA performance for MLP layers across six model dimensions, from a minimal configuration to GPT-2 scale (). Three trends are visible. First, proving time scales sub-linearly: constraints grow by from to (288 to 2,117,632), but proving time increases only (211ms to 4,743ms). This is because Halo2 IPA proving cost is dominated by multi-scalar multiplications whose complexity depends on the circuit degree , not on directly. Second, verification time grows modestly: from 2.8ms to 84.4ms across the same range, remaining practical for real-time use even at the largest scale. Third, proof size grows logarithmically: each doubling of constraints adds approximately 64 bytes (one elliptic curve point), confirming the theoretical bound. The total range is only 3,264–3,712 bytes across a constraint increase.
Note that these are standalone MLP benchmarks where circuit degree scales with . In the full transformer block results (Table 3 in the main text), we fix for all dimensions, which is why prove time there remains flat at 6.2s regardless of —the circuit has the same number of rows, with smaller models simply leaving more rows unused.
C.2 Fisher Selection Strategy Comparison
Table 7 compares three layer selection strategies on TinyLLaMA-1.1B (22 layers) at 50% verification budget (11 layers verified). Fisher selects the 11 layers with highest Fisher information scores. Random selects 11 layers uniformly at random (averaged over 3 random seeds). Uniform selects every other layer (deterministic, evenly spaced).
Fisher selection captures 86.0% of the total Fisher mass (i.e., the sum of Fisher scores of verified layers divided by the sum across all layers), compared to 79.3% for random and 68.6% for uniform. The 6.7 percentage point gain over random comes from Fisher’s ability to identify the few high-importance layers (layers 0–2 in TinyLLaMA) that contribute disproportionately to output sensitivity. Uniform selection performs worst because it is forced to include low-importance layers at fixed intervals.

